│ extractelement. The constructed vector constants and shuffle mask currently   │
│ use poison for lanes that are not relevant to the computation. In LLVM IR     │
│ semantics, poison is a property of the entire value: any use of a poison      │
│ value is poison, regardless of lane. Thus, creating a vector value with any   │
│ poison lane will make the entire vector poison, and extracting a single lane  │
│ from that results in poison even if the targeted lane is defined.\n\nThis     │
│ manifests in the repro because the transform sets all irrelevant lanes to     │
│ poison for both the compare constant vector and the shuffle mask, which       │
│ causes the intermediate vector values (vcmp, shift, binop) to become poison   │
│ and the final extractelement returns poison, while the original scalar code   │
│ was defined.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows the first              │
│ transformation performed by foldExtractedCmps:\n- It replaces scalar          │
│ icmp+ashr on i1 with vector icmp on <4 x i32> against a constant vector       │
│ containing poison in lanes 0 and 2, then shufflevector with a mask that has   │
│ PoisonMaskElem in all irrelevant lanes, followed by ashr on <4 x i1> vectors, │
│ and finally extractelement of lane 1.\nAlive2 reports: Target is more         │
│ poisonous than source. Specifically, the vector compare produced <poison, 0,  │
│ poison, 1>, the shuffle produced <poison, 1, poison, poison>, the vector ashr │
│ propagated poison to all lanes, and the extract yielded poison. The source    │
│ produced a defined 1.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n- Poison lanes in a vector  │
│ value cause the entire vector to be poison in LLVM IR semantics. Using        │
│ PoisonValue elements for the unused compare lanes and PoisonMaskElem in the   │
│ shuffle mask makes the produced vector values poison as a whole. Any          │
│ subsequent use, including extracting a specific lane, yields poison.\n-       │
│ Therefore the transformation is not semantics-preserving. We must avoid       │
│ introducing poison into the intermediate vector values for lanes that are     │
│ irrelevant to the final result.\n\nThe correct approach is to use undef for   │
│ irrelevant lanes. Undef does not poison the value; it represents an arbitrary │
│ but consistent value chosen at use time. Using undef in the constant vector   │
│ and shuffle mask allows the operation to be lane-local and keeps the final    │
│ extracted lane defined while leaving other lanes unconstrained. This matches  │
│ the scalar semantics and preserves correctness.\n\n4. Proposed Edit           │
│ Point(s):\n- Edit Point 1 (lines 1093-1096): Initialize the shuffle mask with │
│ UndefMaskElem instead of PoisonMaskElem.\n  Reasoning: Avoid creating a       │
│ poison shuffle result. Undef mask for unused lanes does not poison the        │
│ shuffle and therefore does not taint the entire vector.\n\n  Edit:\n  -       │
